ies, along with other activities determined by the Director. The selection process involves higher education institutions applying for funding. The selection process for funding under this subsection requires higher education institutions to submit an application detailing their research and instructional capacity. The application must include a description of the applicant's research and instructional capacity, a plan to build instructional capacity in information fields, and the role of each consortium member in implementing the proposal. The application must include a plan to build instructional capacity in information fields, collaborations with government agencies or private industry, and a survey of historic student enrollment and placement data. The application must include a plan to build instructional capacity in information fields, collaborations with government agencies or private industry, and a survey of historic student enrollment and placement data. Additionally, a plan to evaluate the success of the proposed program, including postgraduate assessment of graduate school and job placement, retention rates, and relevance to the workplace, must be provided. The Director will ensure awards are granted accordingly. The Director will ensure grants are awarded in various geographic areas and institutions of higher education. A program evaluation will be conducted three years after its establishment. The Director will evaluate the program established under this subsection three years after its establishment to assess the grants' impact on increasing the quality and quantity of students pursuing degrees in information fields. The assessment will be made publicly available. The Director will evaluate the program established under this subsection to assess the impact on increasing students pursuing degrees in information fields. Authorization of appropriations is provided for fiscal years 2008 to 2011. Grants will be provided under the Scientific and Advanced Technology Act of 1992. The Director will provide grants under the Scientific and Advanced Technology Act of 1992 to improve education in information-related fields. Authorization of appropriations is set at $9,600,000 for fiscal year 2011. Authorization of appropriations for the National Science Foundation under this subsection are as follows: $7,000,000 for fiscal year 2008, $7,200,000 for fiscal year 2009, $7,400,000 for fiscal year 2010, and $7,600,000 for fiscal year 2011. SEC. 6. REPORT ON STANDARDIZATION OF MEASURES RELATED TO DIGITAL INFORMATION. The Director of the National Institute of Standards and Technology must report to Congress on informatics efforts, standards harmonization, research, and support for executive orders on digitization. The report will include timetables for information standards promulgation and major challenges. The National Institute of Standards and Technology must report to Congress on informatics standards development, challenges, and efforts to ensure digital information usability for scientists and researchers. This includes timetables for information standards promulgation and actions to ensure robust and timely standards.
